</section>
<section data-index="1305">
<h5 class="grey" data-index="1306">Intangible Assets</h5>
<p data-index="1307"><span class="glossTerm" data-index="1308"><span class="blue" data-index="1309"><b data-index="1310">Intangible assets</b></span></span> <span data-index="1311">lack physical substance and are not financial instruments (see the “Fair Values” section later in this chapter for the definition of a financial <span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="5-11" id="Page_5-11" data-index="1312"></span>instrument). They include patents, copyrights, franchises, goodwill, trademarks, trade names, and customer lists. A company writes off (amortizes) limited-life intangible assets over their useful lives. It periodically assesses indefinite-life intangibles (such as goodwill) for impairment. Intangibles can represent significant economic resources, yet financial analysts often ignore them, because valuation is difficult.</span></p>
<p data-index="1313"><span class="red" data-index="1314">PepsiCo, Inc.</span> <span data-index="1315">reported intangible assets in its balance sheet as shown in</span> <a class="blue" id="c05-fig-0012-1" href="#c05-fig-0012" data-index="1316" data-section-index="15" data-section-idref="c05-fig-0012" data-target-data-index="1319"><b data-index="1317">Illustration 5.12</b></a><span data-index="1318">.</span></p>
<figure id="c05-fig-0012" data-index="1319">
<table class="table tbc" style=" width: 70%;" data-index="1320">
<tbody data-index="1321">
