<tr data-index="2280">
<td data-index="2281">Cash at end of year</td>
<td data-index="2282"><span class="right" data-index="2283"><span style=" border-bottom: 3px double;" data-index="2284">$XXX</span></span><br data-index="2285"></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<figcaption data-index="2286"><p data-index="2287"><span class="figureLabel" data-index="2288"><b data-index="2289"><a role="doc-backlink" href="#c05-fig-0017-1" data-index="2290" data-section-index="15" data-section-idref="c05-fig-0017-1" data-target-data-index="2245"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="2291">ILLUSTRATION 5.17</span></a></b> <b data-index="2292">Basic Format of Cash Flow Statement</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<p data-index="2293"><a class="blue" id="c05-fig-0018-1" href="#c05-fig-0018" data-index="2294" data-section-index="15" data-section-idref="c05-fig-0018" data-target-data-index="2297"><b data-index="2295">Illustration 5.18</b></a> <span data-index="2296">graphs the inflows and outflows of cash classified by activity.</span></p>
<figure id="c05-fig-0018" data-index="2297">
<img src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c05/w0496.jpg" alt="An illustration shows the inflows and outflows of cash with respect to a cash pool centered in the diagram. A box in the center of the chart is labeled Cash Pool. Three text boxes labeled operating, investing, and financing activities appear above and another three with the same titles appear below the cash pool box. The three boxes at the top represent cash Inflows and the three at the bottom represent outflows. The boxes at the top are inflows of cash and are shown with arrows leading to the cash pool. These are:
Operating Activities, described as when cash receipts, revenues, exceed cash expenditures, expenses; Investing Activities, described as the sale of property, plant, and equipment, the sale of debt or equity securities of other entities, or the collection of loans to other entities; and financing activities which include the Issuance of equity securities, and the Issuance of debt such as bonds and notes.
The boxes at the bottom are outflows of cash and are shown with arrows leading from the cash pool. These are: Operating Activities which are described as, when cash expenditures, expenses, exceed cash receipts, revenues;
Investing Activities which includes purchase of property, plant, and equipment, the purchase of debt and equity securities of other entities, and loans to other entities; and Financing Activities, which include the payment of dividends, the redemption of debt, and the reacquisition of capital stock.   

" data-index="2298" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A935%2C%22height%22%3A582%7D">
<figcaption data-index="2299"><p data-index="2300"><span class="figureLabel" data-index="2301"><b data-index="2302"><a role="doc-backlink" href="#c05-fig-0018-1" data-index="2303" data-section-index="15" data-section-idref="c05-fig-0018-1" data-target-data-index="2294"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="2304">ILLUSTRATION 5.18</span></a></b> <b data-index="2305">Cash Inflows and Outflows</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<p data-index="2306"><span class="bold" data-index="2307">The statement’s value is that it helps users evaluate liquidity, solvency, and financial flexibility.</span> <span data-index="2308">As stated earlier,</span> <span class="bold" data-index="2309">liquidity</span> <span data-index="2310">refers to the “nearness to cash” of assets and liabilities.</span> <span class="bold" data-index="2311">Solvency</span> <span data-index="2312">is the firm’s ability to pay its debts as they mature.</span> <span class="bold" data-index="2313">Financial flexibility</span> <span data-index="2314"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="5-19" id="Page_5-19" data-index="2315"></span>is a company’s ability to respond and adapt to financial adversity and unexpected needs and opportunities.</span></p>
<p data-index="2316">We have devoted <a href="c23.xhtml" data-index="2317" data-section-index="33">Chapter 23</a> entirely to the detailed preparation and content of the statement of cash flows. The intervening chapters will cover several elements and complex topics that affect the content of a typical statement of cash flows. The presentation in this chapter is introductory—a reminder of the existence of the statement of cash flows and its usefulness.</p>
</section>
<section id="h3_1009" data-index="2318">
<h3 data-index="2319"><span class="red" data-index="2320">Preparation of the Statement of Cash Flows</span></h3>
<section data-index="2321">
<h4 data-index="2322"><span class="codeColorBlue2" data-index="2323">Sources of Information</span></h4>
<p data-index="2324"><span data-index="2325">Companies obtain the information to prepare the statement of cash flows from several sources: (1) comparative balance sheets, (2) the current income statement, and (3) selected transaction data.</span> <span data-index="2326">The following example demonstrates how companies use these sources in preparing a statement of cash flows.</span></p>
<p data-index="2327"><span data-index="2328">On January 1, 2020, in its first year of operations, Telemarketing Inc. issued 50,000 shares of $1 par value common stock for $50,000 cash. The company rented its office space, furniture, and telecommunications equipment and performed marketing services throughout the first year. In June 2020, the company purchased land for $15,000.</span> <a class="blue" id="c05-fig-0019-1" href="#c05-fig-0019" data-index="2329" data-section-index="15" data-section-idref="c05-fig-0019" data-target-data-index="2332"><b data-index="2330">Illustration 5.19</b></a> <span data-index="2331">shows the company’s comparative balance sheets at the beginning and end of 2020.</span></p>
